'''Xu Shang-Chi''' ({{IPAc-en|lang|ˈ|ʃ|uː|_|ʃ|ɑː|ŋ|ˈ|tʃ|iː}} {{Respell|SHOO|_|shahng|CHEE}}; {{lang-zh|s=徐尚气|p=Xú Shàngqì}}) is a [[fictional character]] portrayed by [[Simu Liu]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU) [[multimedia franchise]], based on the [[Marvel Comics]] character [[Shang-Chi|of the same name]]. In the franchise, Shang-Chi is the son of [[Ying Li (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Ying Li]] and [[Wenwu]], the founder and first leader of the [[Ten Rings (organization)|Ten Rings]] terrorist organization. Trained to be a highly skilled [[martial arts|martial artist]] and [[assassin]] by his father, alongside his sister [[Xialing]], Shang-Chi left the Ten Rings for a normal life in [[San Francisco]], only to be drawn back into the world he left behind when Wenwu seeks him out.

Shang-Chi has been noted as being the first Asian [[superhero]] to lead a large-budget film, and Liu's portrayal has been positively received. He first appeared in ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' (2021), and will return in the film's sequel. An alternate version of the character is set to appear in the animated series ''[[Marvel Zombies (TV series)|Marvel Zombies]]'' (2024).<ref name="SDCC2022CBR">{{Cite web |last=Nolan |first=Liam |date=July 22, 2022 |title=SDCC Live: Marvel Studios Animation Panel Reveals Future of X-Men '97, What If and Marvel Zombies |url=https://www.cbr.com/marvel-studios-animation-x-men-what-if-zombies-sdcc/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722212921/https://www.cbr.com/marvel-studios-animation-x-men-what-if-zombies-sdcc/ |archive-date=July 22, 2022 |access-date=July 22, 2022 |website=[[Comic Book Resources]]}}</ref>

== Concept and creation ==
The character was conceived in late 1972 by writer [[Steve Englehart]] and artist [[Jim Starlin]].  Marvel Comics had wished to acquire the rights to adapt the ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'' television program, but were denied permission by [[Warner Communications]], who was also the owner of Marvel's primary rival, [[DC Comics]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Sacks |first1=Jason |title=American Comic Book Chronicles: The 1970s |last2=Dallas |first2=Keith |date=2014 |publisher=TwoMorrows Publishing |isbn=978-1605490564 |page=99}}</ref> Instead, Marvel acquired the comic book rights to [[Sax Rohmer]]'s pulp villain [[Fu Manchu|Dr. Fu Manchu]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 3, 2001 |title=A success written in the stars |url=http://www.universohq.com/quadrinhos/entrevista_starlin_eng01.cfm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125065341/http://www.universohq.com/quadrinhos/entrevista_starlin_eng01.cfm |archive-date=November 25, 2010 |publisher=[[Universo HQ]]}}</ref> Englehart and Starlin developed Shang-Chi, a master of [[kung fu]], who was introduced as a previously unknown son of Fu Manchu.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Sanderson |first1=Peter |title=Marvel Chronicle A Year by Year History |last2=Gilbert |first2=Laura |publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-0756641238 |location=London, United Kingdom |page=161 |chapter=1970s |quote=Capitalizing on the popularity of martial arts movies, writer [[Steve Englehart]] and artist/co-plotter [[Jim Starlin]] created Marvel's ''Master of Kung Fu'' series. The title character, Shang-Chi, was the son of novelist Sax Rohmer's criminal mastermind Dr. Fu Manchu. |author-link=Peter Sanderson}}</ref><ref name="mnyc">{{Cite book |last=Sanderson |first=Peter |title=The Marvel Comics Guide to New York City |publisher=[[Pocket Books]] |year=2007 |isbn=978-1416531418 |location=New York, New York |pages=6–7}}</ref> Though an original character himself, many of Shang-Chi's supporting characters were Rohmer creations.  Starlin left the series after #17 (replaced by Paul Gulacy) and Englehart after #19 (replaced by [[Doug Moench]]). No characters from the ''Kung Fu'' television series were officially included in the comic series, though in the #19 issue the character Lu Sun bore such a strong resemblance to [[Kwai Chang Caine]] that to avoid copyright issues, the character was given a mustache throughout the issue.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brian Cronin |title=Shang-Chi: How Marvel Edited a Comic to Hide a Kung Fu Character's Appearance |date=October 27, 2021 |url=https://www.cbr.com/shang-chi-how-marvel-edited-a-comic-to-hide-a-kung-fu-characters-appearance/ |access-date=March 7, 2022 |publisher=Comic Book Resources |publication-date=October 26, 2021 |quote=In #19, Shang-Chi runs afoul of the monstrous Man-Thing, who can burn anyone who experiences fear while touching him. He is saved by a mysterious stranger…[comics illustration]<br>The stranger then introduces himself as Lo Sun…[comics illustration]<br>But because we have eyes, we all know that he is obviously based visually on Carradine's Caine…[comics illustration]<br>This allowed Englehart to have his new creation have a heart to heart with the character that inspired him…[comics illustration]<br>However, Marvel felt that it was TOO obvious of a likeness, especially since ''Kung Fu'' was a show about, you know, kung fu, so after Gulacy finished the issue, Marvel had someone draw a mustache on to Lo Sun throughout the issue. Moench later recalled to Jon B. Cooke in TwoMorrows' Comic Book Artist #7, while noting that no one had ever bothered them during their time together on the series (when they had cameos and facial likenesses of a number of major characters), "There had been an earlier problem when Paul drew David Carradine and they actually had to go over Paul's artwork and put a mustache on the David Carradine character, but for some reason, when we were doing it, it all slipped by and there was never any problem." |archive-date=March 7, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220307213445/https://www.cbr.com/shang-chi-how-marvel-edited-a-comic-to-hide-a-kung-fu-characters-appearance/ |url-status=live }}</ref> With artist [[Paul Gulacy]], Shang-Chi's visual appearance was modeled after that of [[Bruce Lee]].<ref name="CBA7">{{Cite magazine |last=Cooke |first=Jon B. |date=February 2000 |title=A Master of Comics Art - Artist Paul Gulacy and His Early Days at Marvel |url=http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/07gulacy.html |url-status=live |magazine=[[Comic Book Artist]] |publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |issue=7 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021213030/http://twomorrows.com/comicbookartist/articles/07gulacy.html |archive-date=October 21, 2007 |access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> According to Englehart, his name was influenced by his study of the [[I-Ching]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Master of Kung Fu 15-19 - Deadly Hands of Kung Fu 1-2 |url=http://www.steveenglehart.com/Comics/Master%20of%20Kung%20Fu.html |access-date=September 7, 2021 |website=www.steveenglehart.com |archive-date=September 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210907101230/http://www.steveenglehart.com/Comics/Master%20of%20Kung%20Fu.html |url-status=live }}</ref> composed of  [[List of hexagrams of the I Ching#Hexagram 46|升 (shēng)]] meaning "ascending" and [[Qi|chi]] meaning vital energy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Francisco |first=Eric |title=Shang-Chi: Why Marvel's most influential comic disappeared. |url=https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/shang-chi-master-of-kung-fu-history-origins |access-date=August 31, 2021 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |language=en |archive-date=January 28, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220128141822/https://www.inverse.com/entertainment/shang-chi-master-of-kung-fu-history-origins |url-status=live }}</ref>

Shang-Chi first appeared in ''Special Marvel Edition'' #15 (December 1973).<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cooke |first=Jon B. |title=Comic Book Artist Collection: Volume 3 |publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]] |year=2005 |isbn=1-893905-42-X |location=Raleigh, North Carolina |pages=6–7 |chapter=Everybody was Kung Fu Watchin'! The Not-So-Secret Origin of Shang-Chi, Kung-Fu Master!}}</ref>  He appeared again in issue #16, and with issue #17 (April 1974) the title was changed to ''[[Master of Kung Fu (comics)|The Hands of Shang-Chi: Master of Kung Fu]]''. Amidst the martial arts craze in the United States in the 1970s, the book became very popular, surviving until issue #125 (June 1983), a run including four giant-size issues and an annual.<ref>{{gcdb series|id= 2265|title= ''Special Collector's Edition''}}</ref>  In the comics, Shang-Chi is raised by his father [[Zheng Zu|Dr. Fu Manchu]] to be the ultimate assassin for the would-be world conqueror.  After learning Fu Manchu's evil nature, Shang-Chi swears eternal opposition to his father's ambitions and fights him as a force for good.  As the result of Marvel later losing the rights to the Rohmer estate, Fu Manchu was later renamed [[Zheng Zu]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 4, 2014 |title=Benson Unleashes Shang-Chi's "Deadly Hands of Kung Fu" |url=https://www.cbr.com/benson-unleashes-shang-chis-deadly-hands-of-kung-fu/ |website=CBR |access-date=July 7, 2021 |archive-date=August 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805232657/https://www.cbr.com/benson-unleashes-shang-chis-deadly-hands-of-kung-fu/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=August 29, 2021 |title=Shang-Chi: How the MCU's New Hero Was First Connected to the Ten Rings |url=https://www.cbr.com/shang-chi-ten-rings-comic-book-debut/ |access-date=August 29, 2021 |website=[[Comic Book Resources]] |language=en-US |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124639/https://www.cbr.com/shang-chi-ten-rings-comic-book-debut/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Starlin, who was previously unfamiliar with Fu Manchu until [[Larry Hama]] informed him of the [[Yellow Peril|racist nature]] of the Rohmer novels, attributed his early departure from the series due to his embarrassment over the revelation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Zachary |first=Brandon |date=July 19, 2019 |title=Shang-Chi Co-Creator Jim Starlin Hopes 'Embarrassing' Villain Isn't in Film |url=https://www.cbr.com/starlin-shang-chi-movie-fu-manchu-regrets/ |website=CBR |access-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124635/https://www.cbr.com/starlin-shang-chi-movie-fu-manchu-regrets/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In the 2015 "[[Secret Wars (2015)|Secret Wars]]" storyline, a version of Shang-Chi resides in the [[wuxia]]-inspired [[K'un-Lun]] region of [[Battleworld]]. In this continuity, he is the exiled son of Emperor Zheng Zu, master of the Ten Rings, a ruthless martial arts clan that uses mystical powers and techniques based on [[Mandarin's rings|the powers of the Mandarin's ten rings]] from the [[Earth-616|mainstream continuity]].<ref>''Master of Kung Fu'' (vol. 2) #1–4 (2015)</ref><ref name=":0" />

According to [[Ed Brubaker]], the copyright issue was one of the reasons for using [[Wenwu|the Mandarin]] as Shang-Chi's father.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 20, 2020 |title=Friday: Brubaker & Martin on Blending Occult, Noir for New Webcomic |url=https://www.cbr.com/friday-ed-brubaker-marcos-martin-webcomic-interview/ |access-date=August 31, 2021 |website=CBR |language=en-US |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124633/https://www.cbr.com/friday-ed-brubaker-marcos-martin-webcomic-interview/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[Marvel Universe|main continuity]], the Mandarin had a son called [[Temugin]] who was trained in a monastery in martial arts and [[philosophy]], his name is inspired by the real name of [[Genghis Khan]], ancestor of the Mandarin.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 28, 2021 |title=10 Things Only Comic Book Fans Know About Shang Chi's Mandarin |url=https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-iron-man-things-only-comic-fans-know/ |access-date=September 5, 2021 |website=ScreenRant |language=en-US |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124636/https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-iron-man-things-only-comic-fans-know/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

According to [[Margaret Loesch]], former president and CEO of [[Marvel Productions]], in the 1980s [[Stan Lee]] approached [[Brandon Lee]] to play Shang-Chi for a movie or television series starring the character.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Francisco |first=Eric |date=November 23, 2018 |title=Stan Lee Tried to Make a Shang-Chi Movie Starring Bruce Lee's Son |url=https://www.inverse.com/article/51139-stan-lee-shang-chi-movie-or-tv-show-bruce-lee-son |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726150054/https://www.inverse.com/article/51139-stan-lee-shang-chi-movie-or-tv-show-bruce-lee-son |archive-date=July 26, 2019 |access-date=April 23, 2019 |website=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse]] |language=en}}</ref> In 2001, a Shang-Chi film entered development at [[DreamWorks Pictures]] but after failing to materialize by 2004, the rights to the character were reverted to Marvel.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brehmer |first=Nat |date=January 16, 2020 |title=Breaking Down the Deleted 'Blade' Ending Featuring Morbius and Why We Never Got That Sequel |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3601107/breaking-deleted-blade-ending-featuring-morbius-never-saw/ |access-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=January 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117041449/https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3601107/breaking-deleted-blade-ending-featuring-morbius-never-saw/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Marvel Puts Shang Chi In DreamWorks' Hands |url=https://www.awn.com/news/marvel-puts-shang-chi-dreamworks-hands |website=Animation World Network |access-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307155609/https://www.awn.com/news/marvel-puts-shang-chi-dreamworks-hands |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=March 30, 2018 |title=15 Abandoned Marvel Movie/TV Projects That We Never Got To See |url=https://screenrant.com/marvel-movie-tv-projects-abandoned/ |website=ScreenRant |access-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307151037/https://screenrant.com/marvel-movie-tv-projects-abandoned/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2004, David Maisel was hired as chief operating officer of Marvel Studios as he had a plan for the studio to self-finance movies.<ref name="fortune1">{{Cite news |last=Leonard |first=Devin |date=May 23, 2007 |title=Marvel goes Hollywood |page=2 |work=Fortune |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/05/28/100034246/index2.htm |url-status=live |access-date=December 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113165739/http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/05/28/100034246/index2.htm |archive-date=November 13, 2013}}</ref> Marvel entered into a [[non-recourse debt]] structure with [[Merrill Lynch]], under which Marvel got $525&nbsp;million to make a maximum of 10 movies based on the company's properties over eight years, collateralized by certain movie rights to a total of 10 characters, including Shang-Chi.<ref name="lat">{{Cite news |last=Vincent |first=Roger |date=September 6, 2005 |title=Marvel to Make Movies Based on Comic Books |work=Los Angeles Times |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/06/business/fi-marvel6 |url-status=live |access-date=April 12, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221135554/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/06/business/fi-marvel6 |archive-date=December 21, 2014}}</ref>   Following the successes of ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' and ''[[Crazy Rich Asians (film)|Crazy Rich Asians]]'' (both 2018), Marvel fast-tracked development of a ''Shang-Chi'' film, hiring [[David Callaham]] in December 2018 to write the screenplay and [[Destin Daniel Cretton]] to direct in March 2019.<ref name="Callaham">{{Cite web |last=Fleming |first=Mike Jr. |date=December 3, 2018 |title='Shang-Chi' Marvel's First Asian Film Superhero Franchise; Dave Callaham Scripting, Search On For Director Of Asian Descent |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/shang-chi-marvel-studios-first-asian-film-superhero-dave-callaham-kevin-feige-black-panther-1202512660/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181204005815/https://deadline.com/2018/12/shang-chi-marvel-studios-first-asian-film-superhero-dave-callaham-kevin-feige-black-panther-1202512660/ |archive-date=December 4, 2018 |access-date=December 3, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref name="Callaham2">{{Cite web |last1=Galuppo |first1=Mia |last2=McMillan |first2=Graeme |date=December 3, 2018 |title=Marvel Developing Shang-Chi Movie with 'Wonder Woman 1984' Writer |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvel-developing-shang-chi-movie-as-first-asian-lead-1165752 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203220442/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvel-developing-shang-chi-movie-as-first-asian-lead-1165752 |archive-date=December 3, 2018 |access-date=December 4, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref><ref name="THRCrettonMarch2019">{{Cite web |last1=Couch |first1=Aaron |last2=Kit |first2=Borys |date=March 13, 2019 |title=Marvel's 'Shang-Chi' Sets Director Destin Daniel Cretton |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-director-destin-daniel-cretton-1194443 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190316003019/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-director-destin-daniel-cretton-1194443 |archive-date=March 16, 2019 |access-date=March 13, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>  Cretton also contributed to Callaham's screenplay.<ref name="ColliderTeaser">{{Cite web |last=Chitwood |first=Adam |date=April 19, 2021 |title=Marvel's First 'Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings' Trailer Reveals a New Hero and a Familiar Villain |url=https://collider.com/shang-chi-trailer-marvel-movie/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419144814/https://collider.com/shang-chi-trailer-marvel-movie/ |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |access-date=April 19, 2021 |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]}}</ref> [[Chinese Canadians|Chinese Canadian]] actor [[Simu Liu]], who had previously expressed interest in the role, was cast as Shang-Chi in July 2019, which was publicly announced by Cretton and [[Kevin Feige]] days later, along with the film's full title to be ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings''.<ref name="ComicCon2019">{{Cite web |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |last2=Galuppo |first2=Mia |date=July 20, 2019 |title=Marvel Finds Its Shang-Chi with Chinese-Canadian Actor Simu Liu |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-simu-liu-star-at-comic-con-1225856 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721050152/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marvels-shang-chi-sets-simu-liu-star-at-comic-con-1225856 |archive-date=July 21, 2019 |access-date=July 21, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> After he was cast, Liu was called by Feige, saying that Liu's life was "about to change",<ref>{{Cite web |last=Power |first=Tom |date=September 3, 2021 |title=Simu Liu on his life-changing role as Marvel's 1st Asian lead superhero and the end of Kim's Convenience |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/simu-liu-on-his-life-changing-role-as-marvel-s-1st-asian-lead-superhero-and-the-end-of-kim-s-convenience-1.6158125 |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |archive-date=January 12, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220112033430/https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/simu-liu-on-his-life-changing-role-as-marvel-s-1st-asian-lead-superhero-and-the-end-of-kim-s-convenience-1.6158125 |url-status=live }}</ref> having previously petitioning for the role since December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Worgaftik |first=Gabe |date=July 22, 2019 |title=Shang-Chi star Simu Liu asked Marvel about playing Shang-Chi on Twitter 8 months ago |url=https://news.avclub.com/shang-chi-star-simu-liu-asked-marvel-about-playing-shan-1836603273 |website=AV Club |access-date=July 8, 2021 |archive-date=May 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516215501/https://news.avclub.com/shang-chi-star-simu-liu-asked-marvel-about-playing-shan-1836603273 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Characterization ==
[[File:Simu Liu by Gage Skidmore.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Simu Liu]] promoting ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' at the 2019 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]

=== Inspirations and dispelling stereotypes ===
Both being of Asian descent, Cretton and Callaham were cognizant of some of the racial stereotypes surrounding Shang-Chi in the comics, with Liu saying everyone involved was "very sensitive to not have it go into stereotypical territory". Cretton believed the resulting script for ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' was a "really beautiful update" to the character from what began in the comics, and was an authentic story about Asian identity.<ref name="EWApril2021">{{Cite magazine |last=Coggan |first=Devan |date=April 19, 2021 |title=Simu Liu suits up in first look at Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings |url=https://ew.com/movies/shang-chi-and-the-legend-of-the-ten-rings-simu-liu-first-look/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419131805/https://ew.com/movies/shang-chi-and-the-legend-of-the-ten-rings-simu-liu-first-look/ |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |access-date=April 19, 2021 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> Callaham added that there is "no single Asian American voice", and he and Cretton contemplated how the film could speak to "the wider Asian diaspora" and would be "exciting and entertaining, but also personal to all these people".<ref name="EWCoverStoryJul2021">{{Cite magazine |last=Yu |first=Phil |date=July 6, 2021 |title=Simu Liu is hitting new heights with Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings |url=https://ew.com/movies/simu-liu-cover-shang-chi-legend-ten-rings/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210706182002/https://ew.com/movies/simu-liu-cover-shang-chi-legend-ten-rings/ |archive-date=July 6, 2021 |access-date=July 6, 2021 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref>  Cretton likened Shang-Chi to Will Hunting from ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'' (1997), who is a "mixture of masculinity and vulnerability", noting both characters had secrets and superpowers they do not understand while Liu believed that Shang-Chi's struggles with identity were the core of the character, rather than his martial arts skills.<ref name="EWCoverStoryJul2021" /><ref name="LiuMensHealth">{{Cite web |last=Samuel |first=Ebenezer |date=May 19, 2021 |title=Simu Liu Wants You to See Yourself as a Superhero |url=https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a36343557/simu-liu-shang-chi-marvel-superhero/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519183928/https://www.menshealth.com/entertainment/a36343557/simu-liu-shang-chi-marvel-superhero/ |archive-date=May 19, 2021 |access-date=May 20, 2021 |website=[[Men's Health]]}}</ref>

When he was contacted to portray the role, Liu wanted the film to "allow society to see Asian men as powerful, desirable and an aspiration of possibility." Liu used experiences as a child battling stereotypes and '[[microaggression]]s as being relatable to Shang-Chi's character arc of coming to terms with his heritage. He also sought to dispel stereotypes originating from [[Bruce Lee]] films in the 1970s that all Asian men know martial arts, making it clear in an [[Instagram]] caption that "Asian actors don't just do kung fu; but Shang-Chi does. It's one of the many things that flesh out his personality, but it's easily the most challenging from a physical perspective.”<ref>{{Cite web |title=Simu Liu Manifests His Destiny In 'Shang-Chi And The Legend Of The Ten Rings' |url=https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2021/09/01/simu-liu-shang-chi |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=www.wbur.org |language=en |archive-date=January 31, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220131192814/https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2021/09/01/simu-liu-shang-chi |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite knowing little about the character at first, Liu was reassured early in ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings''<nowiki/>'s production that "it was very clear from the get-go that [Cretton] was committed to telling an origin story of a hero [that] was not stereotypical, not a trope, who was fully three-dimensional and had a fully modernized [2021] origin story. In addition to Bruce Lee he also cited [[Jet Li]] as one of his inspirations when approaching the character.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=August 30 |first1=Cary Darling |last2=August 31 |first2=2021Updated |last3=2021 |last4=Am |first4=9:39 |title=Interview: 'Shang-Chi' star Simu Liu shatters the superhero racial ceiling |url=https://preview.houstonchronicle.com/movies-tv/shang-chi-star-simu-liu-shatters-the-16417122 |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Preview {{!}} Houston Arts & Entertainment Guide |language=en-US |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124640/https://preview.houstonchronicle.com/movies-tv/shang-chi-star-simu-liu-shatters-the-16417122 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Character journey and fighting style ===
Shang-Chi leaves the [[Ten Rings (organization)|Ten Rings]] organization for a normal life in [[San Francisco]],<ref name="ComicCon2019" /><ref name="EWApril2021" /> with director [[Destin Daniel Cretton]] characterizing Shang-Chi as a [[wikt:fish out of water|fish out of water]] in the U.S. who attempts to hide that with his charisma,<ref name="EWApril2021" /> and does not know "who he really is".<ref name="DeadlineCrettonShangChi">{{Cite web |last1=Tapp |first1=Tom |last2=D'Alessandro |first2=Anthony |date=June 24, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi And The Legend Of The Ten Rings': 2nd Trailer For Marvel Movie May Reveal Abomination |url=https://deadline.com/video/shang-chi-second-trailer-marvel-disney/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210625133719/https://deadline.com/video/shang-chi-second-trailer-marvel-disney/ |archive-date=June 25, 2021 |access-date=June 26, 2021 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> Shang-Chi changes his name to "Shaun" while living in San Francisco.<ref name="RogerEbertReview">{{Cite web |last=Allen |first=Nick |date=August 23, 2021 |title=Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shang-chi-and-the-legend-of-the-ten-rings-movie-review-2021 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210823182134/https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shang-chi-and-the-legend-of-the-ten-rings-movie-review-2021 |archive-date=August 23, 2021 |access-date=August 23, 2021 |website=[[RogerEbert.com]]}}</ref><ref name="AwkwafinaTHR">{{Cite web |last=Davids |first=Brian |date=August 24, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi' Star Awkwafina on Her Key Role During Casting of Simu Liu's Superhero |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-features/shang-chi-awkwafina-simu-liu-1235002417/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210827223901/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-features/shang-chi-awkwafina-simu-liu-1235002417/ |archive-date=August 27, 2021 |access-date=August 29, 2021 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> Of Shang-Chi's decision to live a normal life, Liu found that "what he does is a little bit extreme. And it's also because he was raised under very extreme circumstances...I can't really fault him from taking extreme measures to get out of that situation."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Simu Liu Interview: Shang-Chi, Brad Allan, And His Marvel Audition |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/simu-liu-interview-shang-chi-brad-allan-marvel-audition/ |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Empire |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124636/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/simu-liu-interview-shang-chi-brad-allan-marvel-audition/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Cretton described ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' as "a journey of stepping into who [Shang-Chi] is and what he's meant to be in this world".<ref name="CrettonFandango">{{Cite web |last=Davis |first=Erik |date=August 16, 2021 |title='Shang Chi' Director Destin Daniel Cretton Reveals New Details About Marvel's Next Big Historic Action Movie |url=https://www.fandango.com/movie-news/shang-chi-director-destin-daniel-cretton-reveals-new-details-about-marvels-next-big-historic-action-movie-754385 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210816154620/https://www.fandango.com/movie-news/shang-chi-director-destin-daniel-cretton-reveals-new-details-about-marvels-next-big-historic-action-movie-754385 |archive-date=August 16, 2021 |access-date=August 16, 2021 |website=[[Fandango Media]]}}</ref>
Since the character does not wear a mask, Liu performed many of his own stunts,<ref name="EWApril2021" /> having to work on his flexibility ahead of filming to do so. Liu also put on {{convert|10|lb|kg}} of muscle for the role.<ref name="LiuMensHealth" /> Liu was knowledgable in [[taekwondo]], [[gymnastics]], and [[Wing Chun]],<ref name="LiuSR">{{Cite web |last=Northrup |first=Ryan |date=August 16, 2021 |title=Shang-Chi Star Simu Liu Got Paid $120 For Stock Photo Modeling Gig |url=https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-simu-liu-model-job-stock-photo/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210904070222/https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-simu-liu-model-job-stock-photo/ |archive-date=September 4, 2021 |access-date=September 4, 2021 |website=[[Screen Rant]]}}</ref> and learned and trained in [[tai chi]],<ref name="LiuTheWrap">{{Cite web |last=Welk |first=Brian |date=August 23, 2021 |title=Simu Liu Explains the 'Mosaic' of Martial Arts Styles Used in 'Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings' (Video) |url=https://www.thewrap.com/shang-chi-martial-arts-fight-sequences-tai-chi-wing-chun/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210904071848/https://www.thewrap.com/shang-chi-martial-arts-fight-sequences-tai-chi-wing-chun/ |archive-date=September 4, 2021 |access-date=September 4, 2021 |website=[[TheWrap]]}}</ref> [[wushu (sport)|wushu]], [[Muay Thai]], [[silat]], [[Krav Maga]], [[jiu-jitsu]], [[boxing]], and [[street fighting]] for the film.<ref name="LiuCulturaGeek">{{Cite web |last=Samaniego |first=Maite |date=August 13, 2021 |title=Shang-Chi y la leyenda de los diez anillos: te contamos cómo se preparó Simu Liu, el protagonista para la película |trans-title=Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings: we tell you how protagonist Simu Liu prepared for the film |url=https://culturageek.com.ar/shang-chi-y-la-leyenda-de-los-diez-anillos-te-contamos-como-se-preparo-simu-liu-el-protagonista-para-la-pelicula/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210819210538/https://culturageek.com.ar/shang-chi-y-la-leyenda-de-los-diez-anillos-te-contamos-como-se-preparo-simu-liu-el-protagonista-para-la-pelicula/ |archive-date=August 19, 2021 |access-date=September 4, 2021 |website=Cultura Geek |language=es-AR}}</ref> Liu called the process of training and performing stunts to be "exhausting. there were a lot of grueling hours...but it was one of the most fulfilling experiences in my life."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mullally |first=William |date=September 5, 2021 |title=Simu Liu opens up about personal battle with anxiety on Shang-Chi set |url=https://www.esquireme.com/content/54877-simu-liu-opens-up-about-personal-battle-with-anxiety-on-shang-chi-set |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Esquire |archive-date=September 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210912164850/https://www.esquireme.com/content/54877-simu-liu-opens-up-about-personal-battle-with-anxiety-on-shang-chi-set |url-status=live }}</ref>  Jayden Zhang and Arnold Sun portray Shang-Chi as a child and as a teenager, respectively.<ref name="SRShangChiCast">{{Cite web |last=Brook |first=Mitch |date=September 3, 2021 |title=Shang-Chi Cast & Character Guide: All New & Returning MCU Actors |url=https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-cast-character-guide/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210903132149/https://screenrant.com/shang-chi-cast-character-guide/ |archive-date=September 3, 2021 |access-date=September 3, 2021 |website=[[Screen Rant]]}}</ref>

For an early sequence in the film where Shang-Chi fights off assassins form the Ten Rings, Cretton took heavy inspiration from the works of [[Jackie Chan]], working closely with choreographers [[Brad Allan]] and [[Andy Cheng]], who were both trained in Chan's stunt team. Cretton stated that his favorite moment of the sequence was  "The jacket stunt...when he’s able to take his jacket off, spin it around and throw his jacket back on. It's a straight nod to Jackie Chan from the stunt team of Jackie Chan."<ref>{{Cite web |last1=September 6 |first1=Peter Hartlaub |last2=September 9 |first2=2021Updated |last3=2021 |title=Behind the scenes of the 'Shang-Chi' bus chase through San Francisco — from the film's director |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/behind-the-scenes-of-the-shang-chi-bus-chase-through-san-francisco-from-the-films-director |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Datebook {{!}} San Francisco Arts & Entertainment Guide |language=en-US |archive-date=September 7, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210907153900/https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/behind-the-scenes-of-the-shang-chi-bus-chase-through-san-francisco-from-the-films-director |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Fictional character biography==
=== Early life ===
Xu Shang-Chi was born to [[Xu Wenwu]], the ancient leader of the [[Ten Rings (organization)|Ten Rings]] organization, and Ying Li, a guardian of the mystical village of [[Ta Lo (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Ta Lo]] in an alternate universe. Shang-Chi's childhood was blissful, with his father renouncing his criminal ways to spend time with his family and his mother entertaining him and his sister Xialing with tales of her village. When Li is murdered by the Iron Gang, old rivals of the Ten Rings, Wenwu takes up his mystical [[Ten Rings (object)|ten rings]] and takes Shang-Chi with him to the Iron Gang's hideout, where he proceeds to brutally massacre the gang.  Wenwu reactivates the Ten Rings organization and has Shang-Chi trained in [[martial arts]] as an assassin under the brutal tutelage of [[Death Dealer (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Death Dealer]]. At the age of 14, Shang-Chi is sent on a mission to kill the Iron Gang's leader and avenge his mother. Despite his success, Shang-Chi is traumatized by the ordeal and flees to [[San Francisco]] to assume a new life, adopting the name "Shaun". He leaves his younger sister Xialing behind with his father. While attending high school, Shang-Chi befriended [[Katy (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Katy]], establishing a close friendship into adulthood.

=== Confronting his past ===
{{Further|Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings}}
10 years later, in present-day,<!-- Do not add "2023" or "2024" without a non-speculatory reliable source or until it gets added to the Disney+ timeline order! --> Shang-Chi is attacked by the Ten Rings led by [[Razor Fist (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Razor Fist]]. Shang-Chi fights them off but loses his pendant given to him by his mother. Fearing that the Ten Rings will attack Xialing for her pendant, Shang-Chi tracks her down and reveals his past to Katy, who agrees to help him. They find Xialing at her [[Street fighting#Underground street fight clubs|underground fight club]] in [[Macau]], but are attacked by the Ten Rings led by Death Dealer, with Wenwu arriving to capture Shang-Chi, Katy, and Xialing after breaking up the fight. The trio are taken to the Ten Rings' compound, where Wenwu reveals that he believes Li is still alive and is being kept in Ta Lo, using the two pendants to create a map that can be used to enter the village. Wenwu plans to destroy the village after freeing Li and imprisons Shang-Chi and the others when they object to his plans.

The trio escape the compound with the help of [[Trevor Slattery]] and his [[hundun]] companion Morris and drive to Ta Lo to warn the village of the Ten Rings. At Ta Lo, Shang-Chi is introduced to his aunt and Li's sister [[Ying Nan]], who explains the history of Ta Lo and reveals that Wenwu is being manipulated by the [[Dweller-in-Darkness (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Dweller-in-Darkness]] into believing Li is still alive so he will use the rings to break the seal imprisoning it. Nan gifts Shang-Chi with an outfit crafted from the red dragon scales of the [[Great Protector]], the [[Chinese dragon|dragon]] guardian of Ta Lo, and teaches him the fighting style of Ta Lo. Shang-Chi defends the village with his new allies when Wenwu and the Ten Rings arrive to destroy the seal. Shang-Chi fights his father, but is defeated and cast into a lake. Shang-Chi is revived by the Great Protector and uses his newfound powers to disarm Wenwu.

After the Dweller escapes its seal, Wenwu sacrifices himself to save Shang-Chi from the Dweller and bequeaths the ten rings to Shang-Chi, who uses them and the Ta Lo fighting style to destroy the Dweller. Shang-Chi later makes a paper lantern and lights it in memory of his father.

Back in San Francisco, Shang-Chi and Katy are summoned by the sorcerer [[Wong (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Wong]] to accompany him to [[Kamar-Taj (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Kamar-Taj]], where they are introduced to [[Bruce Banner (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Bruce Banner]] and [[Carol Danvers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Carol Danvers]] via hologram. Wong, Banner, and Danvers discover that the rings are emitting a mysterious signal and Wong vows to keep looking into it. Shang-Chi then suggests they go to a bar, and he, Katy, and Wong sing karaoke together.

==Reception==
Karen Rought of ''Hypable'' praised the decision to have Shang-Chi already know who he is and what he can do from the very beginning, contrasting with many familiar [[Origin story|origin stories]] seen in other comic-book movies. Of this, Rought noted that "yes, this is an origin story, but it was more about self-acceptance than self-discovery...that was a breath of fresh air for the first film about a new character in the MCU." She described Liu's take on the character to "offers us a perfect dichotomy in his role...He's a kind-faced, goofy, normal guy who hides a secret."<ref>{{Cite web |date=September 6, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi' movie review: Marvel introduces a whole new world |url=https://www.hypable.com/shang-chi-movie-review/ |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Hypable |language=en-US |archive-date=June 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220611094112/https://www.hypable.com/shang-chi-movie-review/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Justin Chang of [[NPR]] was drawn into the character by his complicated relationship with Wenwu, saying that "[Shang-Chi] has a complicated, vaguely Oedipal rivalry with his father, who turned him into the fighting machine he is and subjected him to all manner of cruel manipulation and abuse", demarking the character's "depths of...trauma".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Marvel's 1st Asian Superhero Gets The Full Blockbuster Treatment In 'Shang-Chi' |language=en |work=NPR.org |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/09/01/1032875594/shang-chi-review-marvels-1st-asian-superhero |access-date=September 12, 2021 |archive-date=February 22, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220222075215/https://www.npr.org/2021/09/01/1032875594/shang-chi-review-marvels-1st-asian-superhero |url-status=live }}</ref> Herb Scribner of ''Deseret'' called Shang-Chi "absolutely excellent" and that "he needs to be around for Marvel films for the foreseeable future." Scribner felt that "as Shang-Chi, Liu walks the line of a young man trying to find his way and a vulnerable young boy trying to find his family" and compared the character favorably to other leading characters in the MCU including [[Thor (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thor]] and Bruce Banner.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Scribner |first=Herb |date=August 23, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings' is your next favorite Marvel movie |url=https://www.deseret.com/2021/8/23/22634154/shang-chi-legend-of-the-ten-rings-review |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Deseret News |language=en |archive-date=November 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119124638/https://www.deseret.com/2021/8/23/22634154/shang-chi-legend-of-the-ten-rings-review |url-status=live }}</ref>

After comments from a 2017 interview in which Liu referencing that his parents told him that China was a "third world" country where people were "dying of starvation",a Chinese release for ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' thus became unlikely. This led many Chinese fans to express disappointment that they would not be able to see the movie, citing the film's decision to remove controversial character elements related to Shang-Chi as a positive.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=September 10, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi' China Release Unlikely In Wake Of Unearthed Comments By Star Simu Liu; 'The Eternals' Hopes In Question |url=https://deadline.com/2021/09/shang-chi-china-release-simu-liu-marvel-1234830474/ |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Deadline |language=en-US |archive-date=October 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211019020824/https://deadline.com/2021/09/shang-chi-china-release-simu-liu-marvel-1234830474/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=September 8, 2021 |title='Shang-Chi' fans in China call government decision not to release movie a "tragedy" |url=https://www.newsweek.com/shang-chi-fans-china-call-government-decision-not-release-movie-tragedy-1627012 |access-date=September 12, 2021 |website=Newsweek |language=en |archive-date=January 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220106111540/https://www.newsweek.com/shang-chi-fans-china-call-government-decision-not-release-movie-tragedy-1627012 |url-status=live }}</ref>

